TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Impact of Goal Setting on Survey Returns
AU  - Dossett, Dennis L.
AU  - Latham, Gary P.
AU  - Saari, Lise M.
Y1  - 1980/09/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255521
DO  - 10.5465/255521
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 561
EP  - 567
VL  - 23
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study which explained the impact of organizational deadlines on employee behavior in an industrial setting. The author identifies two hypotheses derived from goal setting theory. The first is the assumption that specific goals lead to higher levels of employee performance. The second deals with the difficulty of attaining goals, stating that specific harder goals elicit higher performance than do easy goals. According to the author, questionnaires and surveys are returned faster when hard goals are set rather than goals that are not enforced.
AB  - The article presents a study which explained the impact of organizational deadlines on employee behavior in an industrial setting. The author identifies two hypotheses derived from goal setting theory. The first is the assumption that specific goals lead to higher levels of employee performance. The second deals with the difficulty of attaining goals, stating that specific harder goals elicit higher performance than do easy goals. According to the author, questionnaires and surveys are returned faster when hard goals are set rather than goals that are not enforced.
