T1  - Impact of the Organization Environment on the Long-Range Planning Process: A Contingency View
AU  - Lindsay, William M.
AU  - Rue, Leslie W.
Y1  - 1980/09/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255507
DO  - 10.5465/255507
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 385
EP  - 404
VL  - 23
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A two-stage survey of 199 corporations in 15 industrial classifications found that firms tend to adopt more complete formal long-range planning processes as the complexity and instability of the business environment increases. These findings were moderated by including the size of the firm as an intervening variable. Other hypotheses dealing with the environment and long-range planning were tested with mixed results.
AB  - A two-stage survey of 199 corporations in 15 industrial classifications found that firms tend to adopt more complete formal long-range planning processes as the complexity and instability of the business environment increases. These findings were moderated by including the size of the firm as an intervening variable. Other hypotheses dealing with the environment and long-range planning were tested with mixed results.
