T1  - The Influence of Personal Factors and Perceived Work Experiences on Employee Turnover and Absenteeism
AU  - Spencer, Daniel G.
AU  - Steers, Richard M.
Y1  - 1980/09/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255522
DO  - 10.5465/255522
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 567
EP  - 572
VL  - 23
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study which examined the relative influence of personal factors and work experiences of employees on employee turnover and absenteeism. According to the results of the study, labor turnover and absenteeism are independent of work experiences and personal factors. The study also determined that absenteeism is predicted more accurately by personal factors than by work experiences. The author notes that personal characteristics exhibit a higher correlations with absenteeism than with turnover.
AB  - The article presents a study which examined the relative influence of personal factors and work experiences of employees on employee turnover and absenteeism. According to the results of the study, labor turnover and absenteeism are independent of work experiences and personal factors. The study also determined that absenteeism is predicted more accurately by personal factors than by work experiences. The author notes that personal characteristics exhibit a higher correlations with absenteeism than with turnover.
